return {
    SoundID = "rbxassetid://18157205257",
    SRTData = "1\n00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,400\nWelcome to the Diepolder Club Panoramic Aquarium,\n\n2\n00:00:03,400 --> 00:00:06,100\nlocated on the beautiful Oregon coast!\n\n3\n00:00:06,300 --> 00:00:09,200\nThe following is an audio tour highlighting some of\n\n4\n00:00:09,200 --> 00:00:11,500\nthe fascinating fish found in the waters of the\n\n5\n00:00:11,500 --> 00:00:14,500\nOregon coast and throughout the Northeast Pacific.\n\n6\n00:00:15,600 --> 00:00:18,600\nThe temperate waters of the Northeast Pacific, located off\n\n7\n00:00:18,600 --> 00:00:21,500\nthe west coast of North America, are home to\n\n8\n00:00:21,500 --> 00:00:25,100\na truly astounding variety of marine organisms.\n\n9\n00:00:25,100 --> 00:00:28,100\nThe area\'s aquatic life comes in a wide range of\n\n10\n00:00:28,100 --> 00:00:32,280\nshapes, sizes, colors, and ecological roles,\n\n11\n00:00:32,500 --> 00:00:36,600\nand the species presented in this aquarium are only a few examples.\n\n12\n00:00:41,700 --> 00:00:44,700\nAlthough it is  a small fish, the blacksmith is\n\n13\n00:00:44,700 --> 00:00:48,100\nlarger than most members of the damselfish family\n\n14\n00:00:48,100 --> 00:00:51,200\nThis species is exclusively found in the Northeast\n\n15\n00:00:51,200 --> 00:00:55,100\nPacific, ranging from Southern Monterey Bay to Central\n\n16\n00:00:55,100 --> 00:00:58,500\nBaja California, and is only found in shallow,\n\n17\n00:00:58,500 --> 00:01:00,700\ncoastal waters throughout its range.\n\n18\n00:01:01,300 --> 00:01:04,900\nBlacksmiths are typically seen with kelp forest habitats\n\n19\n00:01:05,050 --> 00:01:07,950\nfeeding on plankton in the water column during the day,\n\n20\n00:01:08,100 --> 00:01:10,000\nat night they often hide in\n\n21\n00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:12,800\nrocky crevices to avoid nocturnal predators.\n\n22\n00:01:14,100 --> 00:01:17,800\nAnother species of damselfish, and an even larger one,\n\n23\n00:01:17,800 --> 00:01:21,200\nthe garibaldi can be found in the Northeast Pacific.\n\n24\n00:01:21,200 --> 00:01:25,100\nRanging from Monterey Bay to Southern Baja California,\n\n25\n00:01:25,100 --> 00:01:27,800\nthese fish are instantly recognizable thanks\n\n26\n00:01:27,800 --> 00:01:30,600\nto their distinctive bright orange coloration.\n\n27\n00:01:30,600 --> 00:01:33,900\nAs juveniles, they are covered in bright blue spots,\n\n28\n00:01:34,200 --> 00:01:37,200\nalthough these tend to fade away as they reach maturity.\n\n29\n00:01:37,200 --> 00:01:40,000\nAdults of this species form pairs during breeding\n\n30\n00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:42,600\nseason and will attempt to chase away intruders\n\n31\n00:01:42,600 --> 00:01:45,900\nof all sizes from their nests - including much\n\n32\n00:01:45,921 --> 00:01:48,300\nlarger fish and even scuba divers!\n\n33\n00:01:49,500 --> 00:01:52,200\nKelp bass, as their name suggests, are a common\n\n34\n00:01:52,200 --> 00:01:55,500\nsight in the kelp forest of the Northeast Pacific.\n\n35\n00:01:55,500 --> 00:01:57,600\nAlthough they can be seen from the border between\n\n36\n00:01:57,600 --> 00:02:01,600\nWashington and Oregon South to Southern Baja California, they\n\n37\n00:02:01,600 --> 00:02:04,900\nare relatively rare north of Southern California.\n\n38\n00:02:04,900 --> 00:02:08,800\nJuvenile kelp bass prefer eating bottom-dwelling invertebrates\n\n39\n00:02:08,800 --> 00:02:11,700\nsuch as crustaceans, but as they grow, they\n\n40\n00:02:11,700 --> 00:02:13,900\nmove to deeper waters and alter their diet\n\n41\n00:02:13,900 --> 00:02:16,700\nto include more fish and cephalopods.\n\n42\n00:02:17,600 --> 00:02:19,900\nForming a large school in the water column of this\n\n43\n00:02:19,900 --> 00:02:23,000\nexhibit is a group of northern anchovies.\n\n44\n00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:25,100\nThese fish are found in high abundance\n\n45\n00:02:25,100 --> 00:02:27,700\nand are widespread in the Northeast Pacific,\n\n46\n00:02:27,700 --> 00:02:31,400\nranging from Vancouver Island to Baja California.\n\n47\n00:02:31,400 --> 00:02:34,200\nThey feed primarily on planktonic crustaceans\n\n48\n00:02:34,200 --> 00:02:35,800\nand are an important source of\n\n49\n00:02:35,800 --> 00:02:37,900\nfood for many other marine animals.\n\n50\n00:02:39,300 --> 00:02:40,900\nDespite their name, wolf-eels\n\n51\n00:02:40,900 --> 00:02:43,000\nare neither wolves nor eels.\n\n52\n00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:45,000\nThey are one of the largest members of the\n\n53\n00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:48,800\nwolffish family, which includes several other species that would\n\n54\n00:02:48,800 --> 00:02:51,600\ntraditionally be seen as less eel-like.\n\n55\n00:02:51,600 --> 00:02:54,000\nWolf-eels can be found on both sides of\n\n56\n00:02:54,000 --> 00:02:56,900\nthe North Pacific, ranging from the Sea of Japan\n\n57\n00:02:56,900 --> 00:03:00,100\nto the south of the Imperial Beach in California.\n\n58\n00:03:00,100 --> 00:03:03,200\nWhen these fish are young, they are pelagic, drifting\n\n59\n00:03:03,200 --> 00:03:05,600\naround in the open ocean for up to two\n\n60\n00:03:05,600 --> 00:03:08,600\nyears until they settle in a coastal region.\n\n61\n00:03:08,600 --> 00:03:11,000\nOnce a wolf-eel finds a spot to hide,\n\n62\n00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:13,600\nit will continue to occupy that spot for the\n\n63\n00:03:13,600 --> 00:03:16,000\nrest of its life unless it is forced out.\n\n64\n00:03:17,500 --> 00:03:19,500\nAlthough it is related to the deep-sea\n\n65\n00:03:19,500 --> 00:03:23,000\ndwelling Sixgill sharks, the Broadnose sevengill\n\n66\n00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:26,200\nshark is commonly found in temperate, shallow\n\n67\n00:03:26,200 --> 00:03:30,300\nwaters, even entering muddy bays and estuaries.\n\n68\n00:03:30,300 --> 00:03:33,200\nWhile not normally a very fast swimmer, this shark\n\n69\n00:03:33,200 --> 00:03:36,500\ncan move surprisingly quickly when in pursuit of prey\n\n70\n00:03:36,500 --> 00:03:39,400\nthat includes other sharks, bony fish, marine\n\n71\n00:03:39,400 --> 00:03:43,700\nmammals, invertebrates, and even decomposing carcasses.\n\n72\n00:03:43,700 --> 00:03:46,700\nWhile certainly abundant in the northeast Pacific, these\n\n73\n00:03:46,700 --> 00:03:49,200\nsharks are not exclusive to that region and\n\n74\n00:03:49,200 --> 00:03:51,800\ncan be seen in coastal waters worldwide.\n\n75\n00:03:56,900 --> 00:04:00,100\nThese animals exhibited here represent only a small\n\n76\n00:04:00,100 --> 00:04:03,400\nfraction of the biodiversity of the Northeast Pacific\n\n77\n00:04:03,400 --> 00:04:06,400\nand even a smaller fraction of the biodiversity\n\n78\n00:04:06,400 --> 00:04:08,100\nof our planet as a whole.\n\n79\n00:04:08,100 --> 00:04:11,100\nBy taking steps to protect our ecosystems today,\n\n80\n00:04:11,100 --> 00:04:13,100\nwe can help ensure that they\n\n81\n00:04:13,100 --> 00:04:15,300\nwill remain with us in the future.\n\n"
};
